      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can biotin cause acne or breakouts?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'There is anecdotal evidence linking high-dose biotin supplementation to acne breakouts, though the mechanism is not fully established. The leading theory involves competitive absorption: biotin and pantothenic acid (vitamin B5) share the same intestinal transporter, and high-dose biotin supplementation may reduce B5 absorption. Since B5 plays a role in sebum regulation and skin barrier function, a relative B5 deficiency could theoretically increase sebum production and trigger breakouts. If you experience acne after starting biotin, try reducing the dose to 2500mcg or supplementing with an additional 500mg of pantothenic acid to restore the B5 balance.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Does biotin interfere with blood tests?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, this is a clinically significant interaction. High-dose biotin supplementation can interfere with immunoassay-based blood tests, potentially causing falsely elevated or falsely decreased results. The FDA issued a safety communication in 2017 warning that biotin interference has led to at least one reported death due to a falsely low troponin result in a patient experiencing a heart attack. Thyroid function tests, hormone panels, and cardiac biomarkers are the most commonly affected. If you take biotin supplements, discontinue them for at least 72 hours before any blood work and inform your healthcare provider about your supplementation to ensure accurate test interpretation.' },
