    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How long does it take for biotin to work on hair?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most clinical studies and dermatologist recommendations indicate a minimum of 3 to 6 months of consistent daily biotin supplementation before meaningful hair changes become visible. Hair grows at an average rate of approximately half an inch per month, and the hair growth cycle includes a 2 to 7 year anagen (growth) phase. Biotin primarily strengthens hair that is currently in the growth phase by supporting keratin infrastructure, so you need to wait for new growth to replace existing hair before visible thickness and strength improvements become apparent. Nail improvements typically appear faster, within 2 to 3 months, because nails grow at a faster rate relative to their visible length.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is biotin the same as vitamin B7?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, biotin is the common name for vitamin B7, also known as vitamin H (from the German word Haar and Haut, meaning hair and skin). It is a water-soluble B-complex vitamin that functions as a coenzyme for five carboxylase enzymes involved in fatty acid synthesis, amino acid metabolism, and gluconeogenesis. In the context of beauty supplementation, biotin supports keratin production, which is the structural protein in hair, skin, and nails. The vitamin was historically called vitamin H because early researchers noted that biotin deficiency caused dermatitis and alopecia, establishing the direct connection between this nutrient and skin and hair health.' },
