      <span class="key-stat-num">5,000mcg</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">is the most common dose in biotin gummies — <strong>16,667% of the Adequate Intake</strong>. This sounds extreme, but biotin is water-soluble with no established Tolerable Upper Intake Level. Excess is excreted in urine, and clinical studies examining hair and nail benefits use doses in the 2,500-5,000mcg range precisely because the 30mcg AI is set to prevent deficiency, not optimize keratin production.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The gummy format dominates biotin supplement sales because the target consumer — primarily women aged 18-45 seeking hair and nail improvements — strongly prefers the taste and experience of a gummy over swallowing a capsule. This preference has driven explosive growth, making biotin gummies a $400 million market segment in the US alone. But not all biotin gummies deliver equal value, and the difference between the best and worst options is substantial.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Keratin Production</strong>
        <p>Biotin activates carboxylase enzymes that synthesize fatty acids required for keratin protein folding. Without adequate biotin, keratin structure weakens, producing brittle nails that split and hair shafts that break under minimal tension.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>2,500mcg vs. 5,000mcg</strong>
        <p>Both doses appear in clinical literature. 2,500mcg is the minimum used in nail brittleness studies. 5,000mcg is the standard in hair growth research. Higher doses have not shown proportionally better results in published trials.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Deficiency Signs</strong>
        <p>Thinning hair, brittle nails, scaly red rash around eyes and mouth, fatigue, and tingling in extremities. Subclinical deficiency is more common than recognized — up to one-third of pregnant women develop marginal biotin deficiency.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Blood Test Warning</strong>
        <p>High-dose biotin can interfere with immunoassay blood tests, causing false results for thyroid, hormones, and cardiac markers. The FDA issued a safety warning in 2017. Stop biotin 72 hours before any blood work.</p>
      </div>
