    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h3>Biotin Dosing Guide: How Much Vitamin B7 Do You Actually Need?</h3>
      <p>Understanding biotin dosing is essential because the gap between the official Adequate Intake (30mcg) and the supplement doses (2,500-10,000mcg) is enormous. Here is what the science says about different dose levels and their applications.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>30mcg (100% AI)</strong>
          <p>The Adequate Intake established by the NIH to prevent deficiency. Easily obtained through a balanced diet including eggs, nuts, seeds, and salmon. This dose is not associated with cosmetic hair or nail benefits in clinical literature.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>2,500mcg (8,333% AI)</strong>
          <p>The lower clinical dose used in nail brittleness studies. A 1993 study by Colombo and Gerber found that 2,500mcg of biotin daily for 6 months increased nail plate thickness by 25% in patients with brittle nails. The minimum effective dose for beauty applications.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>5,000mcg (16,667% AI)</strong>
          <p>The standard dose in hair growth supplements and the most common amount in biotin gummies. Used in the majority of clinical case reports showing hair regrowth in biotin-deficient individuals. The sweet spot for most consumers targeting hair and nail benefits.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>10,000mcg (33,333% AI)</strong>
          <p>The upper end of commercially available biotin supplements. No additional benefit has been established above 5,000mcg in published research. This dose increases the risk of blood test interference and the theoretical B5 competitive absorption issue. Not recommended over 5,000mcg.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128138;</span>
        <p><strong>Critical blood test warning:</strong> The FDA issued a 2017 safety communication warning that biotin can significantly interfere with immunoassay-based blood tests. At doses of 5,000mcg or higher, biotin can cause falsely high or falsely low results for thyroid hormones, troponin (heart attack marker), vitamin D, and reproductive hormones. Discontinue biotin supplementation for at least <strong>72 hours before any blood work</strong> and inform your healthcare provider that you take biotin supplements.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="warn-box">
        <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
        <p><strong>Biotin does not grow new hair follicles:</strong> Biotin strengthens existing hair by supporting keratin infrastructure and may reduce breakage and shedding. It does not create new hair follicles, reverse androgenetic alopecia (pattern baldness), or regrow hair lost to scarring alopecia. If you are experiencing significant hair loss, consult a dermatologist for diagnosis before relying on biotin supplementation, which only addresses nutritional deficiency as a cause.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- HOW WE TESTED -->
    <div class="tested-box">
      <h3>How We Tested These Biotin Gummies</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Purchased independently.</strong> Every product was purchased at full retail price through Amazon or the brand's direct website. No product was provided free of charge, and no brand was informed of this evaluation in advance.</li>
        <li><strong>Verified biotin form and dose.</strong> We confirmed each product uses D-biotin (the biologically active form) and verified the dose per serving against the supplement facts panel. Some products list biotin as part of a "beauty blend" without disclosing the exact amount — these were penalized in our scoring.</li>
        <li><strong>Assessed third-party testing.</strong> We contacted each manufacturer to request certificates of analysis from independent laboratories. Products with USP, NSF, or Igen certification received higher scores than those claiming only generic "third-party tested" status.</li>
        <li><strong>Evaluated supporting ingredients.</strong> We scored multi-ingredient formulas on whether supporting nutrients were included at clinically relevant doses or merely token amounts for label decoration. Zinc, vitamin C, and B5 were weighted positively based on their established roles in hair and skin health.</li>
        <li><strong>Conducted a 6-month consumer panel.</strong> Six members of our editorial team used each biotin gummy daily and tracked nail strength, hair shedding rates, and subjective hair texture changes at 4-week intervals using standardized evaluation criteria.</li>
        <li><strong>Calculated long-term value.</strong> Cost per serving was computed, and we projected the total 6-month investment (the minimum recommended supplementation period) for each product to give consumers a realistic picture of the financial commitment required to achieve results.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

